    <name>
      <text>Locating Center, Foci, and Vertices of an Ellipse with Given Minor Axis and Eccentricity</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Suppose the endpoints of the minor axis of an ellipse are \(({@x_cord@}, \pm {@y_cord@})\) and its eccentricity is \({@decimalplaces(eccentricity,1)@}\).</p>
<p>Find the coordinates of:</p>

<p>(a) The center, &nbsp; \(C:\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt1]] </p>

<br>

<p>(b) The foci, &nbsp; \(F_1:\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
<p style="margin-left:90px">\(F_2:\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p>

<br>

<p>(c) The vertices of the ellipse, &nbsp; \(V_1:\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]</p>
<p style="margin-left:202px">\(V_2:\) [[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt3]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked Solution</h3>

<p>To find the coordinates of the center, foci, and vertices of the ellipse, we can use the standard form for an ellipse with centre \((x_0, y_0)\),</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px">\(\displaystyle 
\frac{(x - x_0)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y - y_0)^2}{b^2} = 1
\)</p>
<p>where \(a\) is the semi-major axis length and \(b\) is the semi-minor axis length.</p>

<p>The eccentricity \(e\) of the ellipse is given by:</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(\displaystyle 
e = \sqrt{1 - \frac{b^2}{a^2}}
\)</p>

<p>Given that the endpoints of the minor axis are \(({@x_cord@}, \pm {@y_cord@})\), we can use this information to find \(b\) and then calculate \(a\) using the eccentricity.</p>

<br>

<p>(a) To find the center of the ellipse, we can simply find the midpoint of the minor axis:</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(C: \displaystyle  \left(\frac{{@minor_axis_endpoints[1][1]@} + {@minor_axis_endpoints[2][1]@}}{2}, \frac{{@minor_axis_endpoints[1][2]@}{@minor_axis_endpoints[2][2]@}}{2}\right) 
= ({@center[1]@}, {@center[2]@})\)</p>
<p>Then, we can write the equation of this ellipse as,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(\displaystyle 
\frac{(x - x_0)^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1
\)</p>

<br>

<p>(b) The foci of the ellipse can be found using the formula \(c = ae\), where \(c\) is the distance from the center to each focus. 
<br>Since the center is at \(({@center[1]@}, {@center[2]@})\) and the eccentricity \(e\) is given as {@float(eccentricity)@}, we can calculate \(a\) and then use it to find \(c\).</p>

<p>Given \(e = {@decimalplaces(eccentricity,1)@}\), we can rearrange the eccentricity formula to solve for \(a\):</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\( \displaystyle 
a = \frac{b}{\sqrt{1 - e^2}}
\)</p>

<p>Using the endpoints of the minor axis, \( \textstyle  b = \frac{{@minor_axis_endpoints[1][2]@}-({@minor_axis_endpoints[2][2]@})}{2} = {@b@}\) and \(e = {@float(eccentricity)@}\).</p>

<p>Then, for \(a\),</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\( \displaystyle 
a = \frac{{@b@}}{\sqrt{1 - {@float(eccentricity)@}^2}} 
= \frac{{@b@}}{\sqrt{{@float(1 - eccentricity^2)@}}} 
= {@a@}
\)</p>

<p>Now we can find \(c\) using \(c = ae\):</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\( \displaystyle 
c = {@a@} \cdot {@float(eccentricity)@} 
= {@c@}
\)</p>

<p>So, the coordinates of the foci are,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\( \displaystyle 
\left({@center[1]@} \pm {@c@}, 0 \right) 
= \left({@focus1[1]@}, {@focus1[2]@} \right), \left({@focus2[1]@}, {@focus2[2]@}\right)\)
</p>

<br>

<p>(c) The vertices of the ellipse can be found using the values of \(a\) and \(b\), which we already calculated. Since the vertices occur when \(y=0\), we have.</p>

<p style="margin-left:30px">\((x-{@center[1]@})^2 = a^2\)</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(x-{@center[1]@} = \pm a = \pm {@a@}\)</p>

<p>Therefore, the vertices along the major axis are at,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\( \displaystyle  
\left( {@center[1]@} \pm {@a@}, 0 \right) 
= \left({@vertex1[1]@}, {@vertex1[2]@} \right), \left({@vertex2[1]@}, {@vertex2[2]@} \right)\)</p>]]></text>
